## Rule 1: Problem Implementation from Links

When a user shares a link to a DSA problem (LeetCode, HackerRank, etc.):

**DO:**
- Fetch and read the problem description from the link
- Create a comprehensive `main` function with multiple test cases covering:
  - All examples from the problem
  - Edge cases (empty input, single element, minimum/maximum constraints)
  - Normal cases
  - Boundary cases
- Add detailed JavaDoc documentation including:
  - Problem number and title
  - Problem description
  - Constraints
  - Approach explanation
  - Time and space complexity

**DO NOT:**
- Never create the solution class or solution method
- Never implement the actual algorithm/logic
- The user will implement the solution themselves

## Rule 2: Progress Tracking Updates

When the user asks to "summarize" or "update progress tracker":

1. Check the PROGRESS.md file for the last update date
2. Search for all problem files implemented since that date
3. Update PROGRESS.md with:
   - New problems added to Daily Progress Log
   - New row in Problems Overview Table
   - Their approaches
   - Complexity analysis
   - Whether AI assistance was used
   - Update Summary Statistics (total problems, categories, streak)

## Rule 3: Auto-Update on Problem Transition

When the user says phrases like:
- "move to next problem"
- "next question"
- "going to solve [problem name]"
- Shares a new problem link after completing one

**Automatically:**
1. Update PROGRESS.md with the completed problem details:
   - Add new row to Problems Overview Table
   - Add detailed entry in Daily Progress Log
   - Update Summary Statistics
2. Include: date, time, problem name, link, approach, complexity
3. Mark AI assistance status (based on conversation context)

## Progress Tracker Format

### Problems Overview Table Format
Each row should include:
- Sequential number
- Date (YYYY-MM-DD format)
- Problem name with link and number
- Difficulty (Easy/Medium/Hard)
- Category
- Time complexity (Big O notation)
- Space complexity (Big O notation)
